UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '武康路 · 武康大楼（诺曼底公寓）',
  name_en = '武康路 1 号）',
  body = '<p>Located at the five-way intersection of Huaihai Middle Road and Wukang Road, Wukang Mansion was designed by Hungarian-Slovak architect László Hudec in 1924. Originally called "Normandie Apartments" and renamed Wukang Mansion in 1953, it is one of Shanghai''s earliest modern high-rise apartment buildings. The huge "ship-shaped" wedge-shaped volume inserts itself into the intersection; with one basement and eight above-ground floors, the continuous outer corridors and rounded corner stretch from Huaihai Middle Road into the depths of Wukang Road. It is Shanghai''s only surviving 1920s "ship-shaped" apartment. The ground floor hosts arcades and shops — coffee shops, light dining, creative stores, and a small documentary exhibition. After repeated renovations, the contrast between granolithic and red-brick façades is striking, making it the best viewing point for the plane-tree-lined Huaihai Middle Road streetscape and the famed "First Turn in Shanghai."</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'wukang_road_sa_01';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '武康路 · 罗密欧阳台（德利那齐宅）',
  name_en = '原德利那齐宅）',
  body = '<p>Located at No. 210 Wukang Road and built in the 1930s, this was the private residence of Italian merchant Del Nerce. The building is a three-story brick-concrete Western-style house with cream-yellow walls, white window casings, and a small curved iron balcony projecting south from the second floor, facing the plane-tree-lined depths of Wukang Road. Seen from a distance, the balcony with its surrounding walls, vines, and garden forms a highly theatrical scene, hence its popular nickname "Romeo''s Balcony" (literally "Juliet''s Balcony") coined in the 2000s — the most romantic micro-landmark along Wukang Road. The building is privately owned and not open to the interior; visitors can view and photograph the façade from the Wukang Road sidewalk — an unmissable "view along the way" on a Wukang Road City Walk.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'wukang_road_sa_07';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '武康路 · 密丹公寓',
  name_en = 'Medan Apartments）',
  body = '<p>Located at No. 115 Wukang Road, Medan Apartments was funded by the French International Savings Society and designed by the architectural firm A. Léonard &amp; P. Veysseyre in 1924. The building has six above-ground floors (originally four, later added), a brick-concrete structure, with yellow rough-cast cement walls and simple geometric window casings and balconies; the ground floor has a continuous arcade. Overall it shows the typical "Art Deco" early-modern style of the late 1920s. Located in the heart of the former French Concession next to the Ba Jin residence and Wukang Mansion Courtyard, it has long been rented by foreign doctors, engineers, and cultural celebrities. After 1949 it became ordinary residential housing for Shanghai citizens; the first and second floors are partly commercial, with residential units above. The exterior is open to view; the interior is not accessible — a must-stop on Wukang Road''s "Architecture Can Be Read" walk.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'wukang_road_sa_09';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = 'M50创意园（翠绿色）',
  name_en = 'M50创意园（翠绿色） / M50 Creative Park (Emerald-green)',
  body = '<p>M50创意园位于上海市普陀区莫干山路50号，是上海最早的创意产业集聚区之一，也是世界十大艺术区之一、苏州河畔保留最完整的民族工业建筑群。其前身为上海春明粗纺厂等纺织厂房，2004年9月被上海市文化工作会议规划为"莫干山路视觉艺术特色街区"。园内沿街涂鸦密布，云集上百家画廊、艺术工作室、设计公司与创意店铺，被《TIME》杂志亚洲版列为推荐前往的上海文化地标。翠绿色对应其常春藤与新生的工业文艺气质，是"苏州河十二国色"12种国色的第4种。</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'suzhou_creek_twelve_nations_colors_sa_04';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '创享塔（木槿色）',
  name_en = '创享塔（木槿色） / The X Tower Chuangxiangta (Hibiscus)',
  body = '<p>THE X TOWER）位于上海市普陀区叶家宅路100号，地处长寿路商圈，紧邻苏州河畔。前身为1938年由德国人设计建造的宝成纱厂，曾作为日本人在华东最重要的军服缝制基地，留有标志性的瞭望塔。2018年改造升级为以"共享、开放"为理念的创意园区，总建筑面积约29000平方米，集创意工作站、联合办公、餐饮休闲、网红市集与生活体验于一体。木槿色对应其粉紫渐变、温柔且富生命力的春日气息，是"苏州河十二国色"12种国色的第5种。</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'suzhou_creek_twelve_nations_colors_sa_12';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '四川汉代陶石艺术馆（成都博物院一楼）',
  name_en = 'Sichuan Han Dynasty Ceramic & Stone Art Gallery (Chengdu Museum, 1F)',
  body = '<p>Located on the museum''s 1F core, this is China''s only gallery dedicated to Sichuan Han-dynasty pictorial bricks and carved stones. Hundreds of masterpieces from Pengshan, Xinjin, Pixian, and Xindu are organized into four zones: manor-farming and archery-harvest, markets and salt-wells, mythic auspiciousness, and chariots-banquets. The iconic "Archery and Harvest" brick captures a hunter, startled wild geese, and rippling rice fields; the "Salt Well" brick documents the deep-well brine extraction at Linqiong (home of Zhuo Wenjun), the world''s earliest visual record of salt production. Smiling storytellers, drummers, and qin-players in the pottery zone are evidence of Han-era Sichuan''s cheerful, secular folk spirit. Multimedia stations let visitors zoom into brick details and hear expert commentary. ## 详细地址 / Detailed Address 1F East Wing, Chengdu Museum, No.5 Qinghua Road, Qingyang District, Chengdu, Sichuan ## 门票信息 / Ticket Information Free admission with reservation QR code or ID; permanent exhibitions on 1F are open to all ticket holders. ## 开放时间 / Opening Hours Tue–Sun 9:00–17:00 (last entry 16:00); closed Mondays. ## 交通信息 / Transportation</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'sichuan_museum_sa_02';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '远古四川·史前时期展厅（成都博物院二楼）',
  name_en = 'Ancient Sichuan – Prehistoric Era Hall (Chengdu Museum, 2F)',
  body = '<p>This hall is the prologue of the "Hua Chong Jin Guan Cheng" chronological exhibition. The trail begins with the 2.04-million-year-old Wushan Man tooth fossil, moves through Ziyang Man (Palaeolithic), Gaoshan Ancient City, the Baodun culture, and culminates in the Sanxingdui–Jinsha sites—revealing how the Chengdu Plain nurtured China''s earliest, largest, and most imaginative ancient Shu civilization. Highlights include a section model of Baodun''s city wall (~2700 BCE), 4,500-year-old paddy-field remains, and replicas of face-painted pottery pots, bird-head ladle handles, and jade yazhang ritual blades. Immersive projections let visitors "enter" ancient Shu sacrificial grounds, understanding Sanxingdui–Jinsha not as alien imports but as the indigenous pinnacle of Sichuan''s own civilizational arc. ## 详细地址 / Detailed Address 2F West Wing, Chengdu Museum, No.5 Qinghua Road, Qingyang District, Chengdu, Sichuan ## 门票信息 / Ticket Information Free admission with reservation QR or ID. ## 开放时间 / Opening Hours Tue–Sun 9:00–17:00 (last entry 16:00); closed Mondays. ## 交通信息 / Transportation</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'sichuan_museum_sa_03';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '古代四川·先秦至秦汉三国展厅（成都博物院二楼）',
  name_en = 'Ancient Sichuan – Pre-Qin to Qin-Han-Three Kingdoms Hall (Chengdu Museum, 2F)',
  body = '<p>This hall is Chapter 2 of the "Hua Chong Jin Guan Cheng" chronological exhibition. The narrative moves from the legendary Twelve Shu Kings (Cancong, Du Yu, Kaiming) to the Qin conquest of Ba and Shu (316 BCE), the "colonization of Shu" policies, Li Bing''s construction of Dujiangyan (256 BCE), Wen Weng''s schools, and Han-era artifacts—the Li Bing stone statue, storyteller figurines, and cliff-tomb models. A Dujiangyan sand-table with dynamic water projection reveals the engineering genius of Yuzui, Feishayan, and Baopingkou. The finale explores Three Kingdoms Shu—Shu brocade, Zhuge crossbow, and the zhi-bai coin—showing how the "Land of Abundance" moved from periphery to center stage in the Han–Three Kingdoms era. Allow at least 40 minutes for the dense exhibits. ## 详细地址 / Detailed Address 2F West Wing, Chengdu Museum, No.5 Qinghua Road, Qingyang District, Chengdu, Sichuan (continuous with "Ancient Sichuan" hall) ## 门票信息 / Ticket Information Free admission with reservation QR or ID. ## 开放时间 / Opening Hours Tue–Sun 9:00–17:00 (last entry 16:00); closed Mondays. ## 交通信息 / Transportation</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'sichuan_museum_sa_04';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '巴蜀青铜器馆（成都博物院二楼）',
  name_en = 'Ba-Shu Bronze Ware Gallery (Chengdu Museum, 2F)',
  body = '<p>D铜壶模型、放大纹饰、对比三星堆青铜面具的造型差异，看懂巴蜀青铜与中原青铜"同源异流"的关系。 This is one of the most academically rich galleries in the museum. The collection focuses on late Warring States to early Western Han Ba-Shu bronzes, organized into ritual, weapon, musical, daily-use, and coin categories. The headline piece—the "Inlaid Bronze Pot with Banquet, Music, Water and Land Battle Scenes"—stands ~40 cm tall and uses metal inlay to depict five scenes (mulberry-picking, archery, feasting, water battle, land battle) with nearly 200 miniature figures, hailed as "the earliest bronze War and Peace." Tiger-pattern ge-daggers, willow-leaf swords, and boat-coffin bronze plaques reflect Ba-Shu''s tiger worship and fishing-hunting culture. Multimedia stations let visitors rotate 3D models, zoom inlay details, and compare the lineage differences between Ba-Shu and Central Plains bronzes. ## 详细地址 / Detailed Address 2F Central Wing, Chengdu Museum, No.5 Qinghua Road, Qingyang District, Chengdu, Sichuan ## 门票信息 / Ticket Information Free admission with reservation QR or ID. ## 开放时间 / Opening Hours Tue–Sun 9:00–17:00 (last entry 16:00); closed Mondays. ## 交通信息 / Transportation</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'sichuan_museum_sa_05';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '陶瓷馆（成都博物院二楼）',
  name_en = 'Ceramics Gallery (Chengdu Museum, 2F)',
  body = '<p>Located on 2F East Wing, the gallery chronologically presents ~400 representative pieces: Han green-glazed pottery, Tang Qingyao tri-colors, Song-Yuan Jingdezhen bluish-white porcelain, Ming-Qing blue-and-white and wucai, and late-Qing/Republic qianjiang enamels. The Qionglai (Qingyao) kiln takes center stage—China''s largest southwestern folk kiln system, whose oil-saving lamps, stamped stem-cups, and flambé-glaze bowls were praised by Lu You''s "Laoxue''an Notes." A multimedia reconstruction of the Shifangtang kiln site lets visitors follow clay-purifying, throwing, glazing, firing, and unloading steps. The finale showcases "export porcelain" from Chengdu customs and the Ya''an Tea-Horse Road, revealing Chengdu''s role as a tea-horse corridor and Southern Silk Road hub in East-West ceramic trade. ## 详细地址 / Detailed Address 2F East Wing, Chengdu Museum, No.5 Qinghua Road, Qingyang District, Chengdu, Sichuan ## 门票信息 / Ticket Information Free admission with reservation QR or ID. ## 开放时间 / Opening Hours Tue–Sun 9:00–17:00 (last entry 16:00); closed Mondays. ## 交通信息 / Transportation</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'sichuan_museum_sa_06';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '张大千书画馆·大风堂（成都博物院二楼）',
  name_en = 'Zhang Daqian Painting & Calligraphy Gallery – Dafengtang (Chengdu Museum, 2F)',
  body = '<p>Zhang Daqian (1899–1983) is one of the 20th century''s most internationally influential Chinese painters. The museum—located in his long-time creative base of Chengdu—hosts the Dafengtang memorial hall, displaying his artistic evolution in three phases. Early works like "Lotus" and "Imitation of Shitao Landscape" reveal literati elegance; the mid-period features 1:1 copies of Dunhuang Mogao frescoes and previously unpublished sketch drafts from his 1941–43 pilgrimage; the late-period showcases splash-ink and splash-color masterpieces such as "Ten-Thousand Li of the Yangtze," "Peach Blossom Spring," and "Love-Traces Lake." The gallery''s vitrine also displays Daqian''s personal brushes, seals, palette, and Panama hat—primary sources for biographical research. ## 详细地址 / Detailed Address 2F East Wing (north of Ceramics Gallery), Chengdu Museum, No.5 Qinghua Road, Qingyang District, Chengdu, Sichuan ## 门票信息 / Ticket Information Free admission with reservation QR or ID. ## 开放时间 / Opening Hours Tue–Sun 9:00–17:00 (last entry 16:00); closed Mondays. ## 交通信息 / Transportation</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'sichuan_museum_sa_07';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '书画馆（成都博物院二楼）',
  name_en = 'Painting & Calligraphy Gallery (Chengdu Museum, 2F)',
  body = '<p>Echoing the Zhang Daqian hall, this gallery is organized into four themes: Song academic style, Yuan literati, Ming-Qing Ba-Shu masters, and modern Shu-connected artists. Highlights include rubbing-and-original editions of Su Shi''s "Gongfu Tie," Wen Tong''s "Huzhou Bamboo School" ink-bamboos, Yang Shen''s running-script, works by Tang Yin, Wen Zhengming, Dong Qichang, plus modern masters with Shu ties—Kang Youwei, Liang Qichao, Yu You-ren, Guo Moruo, Xu Beihong, Qi Baishi, and Huang Binhong. Museum-grade temperature-controlled vitrines rotate exhibits seasonally: Spring Festival couplets, Duanwu fan paintings, and an autumn Ba-Shu master show. Digital kiosks allow searching the museum''s full calligraphy and painting archive by dynasty, author, or theme. ## 详细地址 / Detailed Address 2F East Wing, Chengdu Museum, No.5 Qinghua Road, Qingyang District, Chengdu, Sichuan ## 门票信息 / Ticket Information Free admission with reservation QR or ID. ## 开放时间 / Opening Hours Tue–Sun 9:00–17:00 (last entry 16:00); closed Mondays. ## 交通信息 / Transportation</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'sichuan_museum_sa_08';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '藏传佛教文物馆（成都博物院三楼）',
  name_en = 'Tibetan Buddhist Artifacts Gallery (Chengdu Museum, 3F)',
  body = '<p>Located on 3F West Wing, this hall reflects Sichuan''s role as a Sino-Tibetan cultural hub. The collection centers on Ming-Qing gilt-bronze statues, thangkas, mandalas, ritual implements, dharma bells, gyaling horns, and Tibetan sutra woodblocks, organized by five major schools: Tsongkhapa lineage, Gelug, Nyingma, Sakya, and Kagyu. The highlight is an ~80 cm Yongle-era (Ming) imperial gilt-bronze Buddha of extraordinary craftsmanship; alongside a set of 13 ~1.5m × 1m thangkas depicting the Life of Shakyamuni, still vibrant after five centuries. An interactive "mani wheel" wall lets visitors spin carved wooden prayer wheels and experience daily Tibetan Buddhist practice. The hall is the best window into western Sichuan Tibetan-region culture and history. ## 详细地址 / Detailed Address 3F West Wing, Chengdu Museum, No.5 Qinghua Road, Qingyang District, Chengdu, Sichuan ## 门票信息 / Ticket Information Free admission with reservation QR or ID. ## 开放时间 / Opening Hours Tue–Sun 9:00–17:00 (last entry 16:00); closed Mondays. ## 交通信息 / Transportation</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'sichuan_museum_sa_09';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '万佛寺石刻馆（成都博物院三楼）',
  name_en = 'Wanfo Temple Stone Sculpture Gallery (Chengdu Museum, 3F)',
  body = '<p>Wanfo Temple, near Tongjin Bridge outside Chengdu''s west gate, was one of the city''s most important official temples from the Southern Dynasties through the Tang. Excavated in four campaigns between 1882 and 1953, the site yielded hundreds of sculpture fragments—the most important Southern Dynasties Buddhist stone-carving discovery in southern China after Yungang and Longmen. The gallery is organized into five periods: Liang, Northern Zhou, Sui, Early Tang, and High Tang. Highlights include a 523 CE Liang Pingtong-4 statue, Ashoka-style pagodas, a Sui Daye Amitabha, an Early Tang yab-yum Buddha, and a High Tang guardian figure. Wanfo carvings uniquely merge the "Cao Yi Chu Shui" (Cao-style flowing-drapery) and "Wu Dai Dang Feng" (Wu-style fluttering-ribbon) styles—key evidence for the "Southern Dynasties sinicization" of Chinese Buddhist sculpture. ## 详细地址 / Detailed Address 3F Central Wing, Chengdu Museum, No.5 Qinghua Road, Qingyang District, Chengdu, Sichuan ## 门票信息 / Ticket Information Free admission with reservation QR or ID. ## 开放时间 / Opening Hours Tue–Sun 9:00–17:00 (last entry 16:00); closed Mondays. ## 交通信息 / Transportation</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'sichuan_museum_sa_10';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '四川民族文物馆（成都博物院三楼）',
  name_en = 'Sichuan Ethnic Cultural Relics Gallery (Chengdu Museum, 3F)',
  body = '<p>This gallery is the museum''s premier window into the "diverse yet unified" Chinese nation on Sichuan soil. Sections cover Tibetan (Jiarong, Amdo, Khampa), Qiang, Yi (Liangshan), Miao, Tujia, Naxi, Lisu, Mongol, Hui, and Manchu groups. Costumes are the highlights: Jiarong Tibetan women''s colorful robes with turquoise-coral-amber headdresses, Liangshan Yi men''s "chaerwa" woolen cloaks and "tianbaba" hero-knot, Qiang cross-stitch embroidery and silver plaques, Miao pleated skirts and batik, and Tujia "Xilankapu" brocade. The gallery also displays ethnic musical instruments (Qiang flute, mouth harp, long-necked qin, mabu), ritual objects (Bon-buddhist butter flowers, Bimo divining cylinders, Dongba scriptures), tools, and wedding items. The closing "ethnic unity" relief wall embodies the vision of a Chinese national community. ## 详细地址 / Detailed Address 3F East Wing, Chengdu Museum, No.5 Qinghua Road, Qingyang District, Chengdu, Sichuan ## 门票信息 / Ticket Information Free admission with reservation QR or ID. ## 开放时间 / Opening Hours Tue–Sun 9:00–17:00 (last entry 16:00); closed Mondays. ## 交通信息 / Transportation</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'sichuan_museum_sa_11';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '工艺美术馆（成都博物院三楼）',
  name_en = 'Arts & Crafts Gallery (Chengdu Museum, 3F)',
  body = '<p>Located at the end of 3F East Wing, the gallery brings together over ten Ba-Shu craft genres: Shu brocade, Shu embroidery, Chengdu lacquerware, silver filigree, bamboo weaving, porcelain-bamboo composite, ivory and jade carving, gold-silver inlay, paper-cut, shadow puppetry, and masks. The center stage replicates a late-Qing Shu-brocade "great-flower-loom" wooden machine—heritage inheritors demonstrate "picking-and-tying pattern cards" at scheduled times, letting visitors watch "wanzi" and "bing-mei" patterns take form. The double-sided Shu-embroidered panda won the Hundred Flowers Gold Award; the silver-filigree showcase displays "flat-fill" filigree of intricate complexity; the porcelain-bamboo pieces wrap hairlike bamboo strips around thin porcelain. The closing "Intangible Heritage Experience Zone" offers Shu-embroidered fans, silver filigree, and paper-cut classes—reserve at the service desk. ## 详细地址 / Detailed Address 3F East Wing (end), Chengdu Museum, No.5 Qinghua Road, Qingyang District, Chengdu, Sichuan ## 门票信息 / Ticket Information Free admission with reservation QR or ID. Intangible-heritage classes require separate desk booking; some sessions cost ¥10–¥50. ## 开放时间 / Opening Hours Tue–Sun 9:00–17:00 (last entry 16:00); closed Mondays. ## 交通信息 / Transportation</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'sichuan_museum_sa_12';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '刘备殿——汉昭烈庙正殿（成都武侯祠）',
  name_en = 'Liu Bei''s Hall — Main Hall of Han Zhao Lie Miao (Chengdu Wuhou Shrine)',
  body = '<p>Liu Bei''s Hall is the 3rd bay of the central axis, ~12m high, hung with the plaque "Ye Shao Gao Guang." Centered is the gilded seated statue of Emperor Zhaolie Liu Bei—robed, holding the jade tablet, dignified—the shrine''s principal deity. Flanking the emperor are Guan Yu''s three generations (Guan Ping, Guan Xing, Zhang Zun) and Zhang Fei''s three generations (Zhang Bao, Zhang Zun); the side walls display 14 Shu Han elite statues (Zhuge Liang, Pang Tong, Zhao Yun, Ma Chao, Huang Zhong). The stone balustrade is finely carved, and the hall houses historic plaques including Zhuge Liang''s "Collection" plaque and Lu You''s poetry stele. Liu Bei''s birthday celebration is held on the 26th day of the 6th lunar month. ## 详细地址 / Detailed Address Third Bay of Heritage Zone, Wuhou Shrine Museum, No.231 Wuhouci Avenue, Wuhou District, Chengdu, Sichuan ## 门票信息 / Ticket Information Free with heritage-zone ticket; Liu Bei birthday ceremonies require separate ticket. ## 开放时间 / Opening Hours 09:00–18:00 (last entry 17:00); extended to 21:00 on Liu Bei''s birthday. ## 交通信息 / Transportation</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chengdu_wuhou_sa_04';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '惠陵——蜀汉昭烈帝刘备与甘、吴二皇后合葬陵',
  name_en = 'Hui Ling — Joint Burial Tomb of Emperor Zhaolie Liu Bei and Empresses Gan & Wu',
  body = '<p>Hui Ling is located at the northwest of the heritage zone, distributed in a "reverse pinwheel" layout with Han Zhao Lie Miao and Wuhou Shrine. The burial mound is ~12m high, 180m in circumference, ~3,000 sqm. Liu Bei was entombed here after his death at Baidi City in 223 AD—the tomb has never been looted in 1,780 years, protected by both the people''s loyalty and the Ming-Qing tomb guardians. The 1953 excavation of the tomb passage revealed gold, jade, swords, and horse-and-chariot artifacts. The mound, tomb passage, que-fang, and corner towers form a complete imperial-tomb architectural group. ## 详细地址 / Detailed Address Northwest of Heritage Zone, Wuhou Shrine Museum, No.231 Wuhouci Avenue, Wuhou District, Chengdu, Sichuan ## 门票信息 / Ticket Information Free with heritage-zone ticket; tomb passage is closed to the public (heritage protection); memorial ceremonies by appointment. ## 开放时间 / Opening Hours 09:00–18:00 (last entry 17:00); extended to 20:00 in summer. ## 交通信息 / Transportation</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chengdu_wuhou_shrine_sa_09';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '灵祖殿',
  name_en = '灵祖殿 / Lingzu Hall (Patriarch Hall)',
  body = '<p>The Lingzu Hall is located after the Mountain Gate and before the Hunyuan Hall, and is the first main hall on the central axis of Qingyang Palace, as well as the first large hall that visitors see after entering the core sacrificial area of Qingyang Palace. The Lingzu Hall is a single-eave Xieshan-style brick and wood structure, with gray tiles, red walls, flying eaves, five bays wide, and a solemn atmosphere. The main worship in the hall is the Taoist "Sanqing" one of the "Lingbao Tianzun" (Heavenly Worthy of Spiritual Treasure), also known as "Shangqing Lingbao Tianzun", one of the highest deities in Taoism. The two sides of the Lingzu Hall are often accompanied by Taoist Dharma protector generals, with various shapes and exquisite painted statues. In front of the hall, there is a large incense burner, where pilgrims and visitors burn incense to worship and pray for blessings. The Lingzu Hall plays a transitional role in the overall architectural pattern of Qingyang Palace - it not only continues the "separation of secular and sacred" of the mountain gate, but also paves the way for the rituals of the Hunyuan Hall, Sanqing Hall and other main halls behind. The plaques and couplets inside and outside the hall are mostly written by famous Qing dynasty calligraphers, containing rich Taoist cultural connotations. The Lingzu Hall has been bustling with incense all year round, and is an important place to experience the Taoist atmosphere of Qingyang Palace and understand Taoist etiquette.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'area_lingzu_hall';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '混元殿',
  name_en = '混元殿 / Hunyuan Hall (Primordial Chaos Hall)',
  body = '<p>The Hunyuan Hall is located after the Lingzu Hall and before the Bagua Pavilion, and is the second main hall on the central axis of Qingyang Palace. The Hunyuan Hall was first built in the Ming Dynasty and rebuilt during the Kangxi period of the Qing Dynasty. It is one of the oldest and most historically valuable halls in Qingyang Palace. The word "Hunyuan" comes from the Taoist classic "Dao De Jing" (Tao Te Ching) "The Tao gives birth to one, one gives birth to two, two gives birth to three, three gives birth to all things" cosmology, symbolizing the original state of heaven and earth not yet divided and chaos at the beginning. The main deity in the hall is the "Dao De Tianzun" (Heavenly Worthy of the Way and its Virtue), one of the "Sanqing" in Taoism, i.e. Laozi Li Er, the philosopher of the Spring and Autumn Period. In the center of the hall, a bronze statue of Laozi is enshrined, holding a ruyi in his left hand and pressing his knee with his right hand, looking peaceful. The statue of Laozi is one of the treasures of Qingyang Palace, and it is said that on the 15th day of the second lunar month, the birthday of Laozi, a grand birthday ceremony will be held in the palace. The Hunyuan Hall is a single-eave Xieshan-style building, with exquisite Taoist ridge beasts on the roof, and the wood carvings, brick carvings and stone carvings inside and outside the hall are exquisite, integrating the architectural aesthetics of the Ming and Qing dynasties. In front of the Hunyuan Hall, Taoists often chant sutras and confess here, which is an important place to experience the core connotation of the Taoist culture of Qingyang Palace.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'area_hunyuan_hall';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '八卦亭',
  name_en = '八卦亭 / Bagua Pavilion (Eight Trigrams Pavilion)',
  body = '<p>The Bagua Pavilion is located after the Hunyuan Hall and before the Sanqing Hall, and is one of the most iconic buildings in Qingyang Palace, as well as a perfect combination of the architectural art and Taoist philosophy of Qingyang Palace. The Bagua Pavilion is a double-eave octagonal pyramidal building, and the body of the pavilion is mainly decorated with green glazed tiles - the eight sides of the pavilion roof and the eight sides of the pavilion body correspond to the eight trigrams of Qian, Kun, Zhen, Xun, Kan, Li, Gen and Dui. The center of the pavilion roof is a black and white Taiji diagram, with the Yin and Yang fish of the Taiji embracing and rotating, symbolizing the cosmic evolution of "The Tao gives birth to one, one gives birth to two, two gives birth to three, three gives birth to all things". The whole Bagua Pavilion has a unique shape and elegant color, the green glazed tiles shine in the sun, forming a sharp contrast with the surrounding red walls and gray tiles, and is a masterpiece of traditional Chinese Taoist temple architectural art. The pavilion originally enshrined a bronze statue of Laozi riding a green ox through Hangu Pass (which was moved to another place during some periods), which is the core cultural symbol of Qingyang Palace. The Bagua Pavilion is not only the visual "commanding height" of Qingyang Palace, but also carries the Taoist cosmology of "the unity of heaven and man" - visitors standing under the pavilion and looking up at the Taiji diagram can intuitively feel the core idea of "Tao follows nature" in Taoism. The square in front of the pavilion often hosts Taoist cultural exhibitions and Tai Chi performances, making it a must-visit place to experience the Taoist culture of Qingyang Palace.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'area_bagua_pavilion';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '三清殿',
  name_en = '三清殿 / Sanqing Hall (Three Pure Ones Hall)',
  body = '<p>The Sanqing Hall is located after the Bagua Pavilion and before the Doumu Hall, and is the largest and most prestigious hall in Qingyang Palace, as well as the core main hall of the entire Qingyang Palace building complex. The Sanqing Hall is a large double-eave Xieshan-style brick and wood structure, with gray tiles, red walls, carved beams and painted rafters, magnificent and solemn. The main deities in the hall are the highest Taoist gods "Sanqing": Yuqing Yuanshi Tianzun (Heavenly Worthy of the Primordial Beginning), Shangqing Lingbao Tianzun (Heavenly Worthy of Spiritual Treasure), and Taiqing Dao De Tianzun (Heavenly Worthy of the Way and its Virtue, i.e. Laozi). The three pure ones sit side by side on a lotus platform, each Tianzun statue is several meters tall, with a peaceful expression and deep eyes. The plaque "Sanqing Hall" in the hall is written by a famous calligrapher in the Qing Dynasty, vigorous and powerful. The stone steps, moon platforms and railings in front of the Sanqing Hall are all carved from white marble, echoing the Taoist statues and painted murals in the hall, forming the most solemn and sacred sacrificial space in Qingyang Palace. Every year during major Taoist festivals such as the Spring Festival and the birthday of the Sanqing, a grand Zhaijiao ceremony will be held in front of the Sanqing Hall, which is the most concentrated place for Taoist cultural activities in Qingyang Palace. The Ming and Qing wood carvings, stone carvings and paintings inside and outside the hall are of high artistic value, and are precious objects for studying the history of Chinese Taoist architecture and art. The Sanqing Hall is the core place for visitors to understand Qingyang Palace and the highest deity system of Taoism. Visitors are advised to keep quiet and respect religious etiquette when visiting.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'area_sanqing_hall';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '斗姥殿',
  name_en = '斗姥殿 / Doumu Hall (Mother of the Big Dipper Hall)',
  body = '<p>The Doumu Hall is located after the Sanqing Hall and before the Jade Emperor Hall, and is one of the core halls on the central axis of Qingyang Palace. The Doumu Hall is a single-eave Xieshan-style brick and wood structure, with gray tiles, red walls, and a solemn atmosphere. The main deity in the hall is Doumu Yuanjun, also known as "Doumou Yuanjun", the highest goddess in the Taoist star worship system, who is in charge of the constellations in the sky, fertility and longevity in the mortal world. The image of Doumu Yuanjun is unique, with three faces and four heads, or three faces and eight heads, holding the sun and moon in her hands or holding the sun and moon beads, symbolizing her supreme divine power over the stars of the heavens. On both sides of the Doumu Hall are often accompanied by the "Big Dipper Seven Star Lords" - the statues of the seven star lords Tianshu, Tianxuan, Tianji, Tianquan, Yuheng, Kaiyang and Yaoguang. The Doumu Hall has a very high status in folk beliefs, and it is said that Doumu Yuanjun is one of the incarnations of the "Goddess of Child Giving", and pilgrims often pray here for offspring, health and longevity. Every year on the ninth day of the ninth lunar month, the birthday of Doumu, a grand blessing ceremony will be held in front of the hall. The Taoist statues and painted murals in the Doumu Hall are exquisite, and the stone and wood carvings outside the hall are exquisite. The Doumu Hall is a representative place to experience the Taoist star worship and female deity belief in Qingyang Palace, and is also a popular hall for visitors to pray and make wishes.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'area_doumu_hall';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '茶园与老庄书院',
  name_en = '茶园与老庄书院 / Tea Garden and Laozhuang Academy (Lao-Zhuang Academy)',
  body = '<p>The Tea Garden and Laozhuang Academy are located in the middle and rear of the Qingyang Palace building complex, near the back gate of Qingyang Palace, and are the most leisurely characteristic cultural space in Qingyang Palace. The Tea Garden is a typical Sichuan-Western folk-style teahouse building, with green bricks, gray tiles, rattan chairs, bamboo tables, and green plants. The tea garden provides authentic Chengdu gaiwan tea (Bitan Piaoxue, Zhuyeqing, etc.), Sichuan-Western snacks (San Da Pao, Zhong Dumplings, Lai Tangyuan, Fuqi Feipian, etc.), Sichuan-style cold dishes and health tea. Visitors can rest in the tea garden after visiting the halls, brew a pot of tea, taste some snacks, listen to a section of Sichuan opera Qingyin, watch a tea art performance, and experience the most authentic "teahouse culture" in Chengdu. The Laozhuang Academy is adjacent to the tea garden and is a special academic space for displaying, researching and disseminating Taoist culture in Qingyang Palace. The academy is named after the two representative figures of Taoism - Laozi (Li Er) and Zhuangzi (Zhuang Zhou). The academy has a collection of Taoist classic versions such as the "Tao Te Ching" and "Zhuangzi", Taoist calligraphy stone inscriptions and rubbings from past dynasties, and books on Taoist culture research. The cloister outside the academy often has calligraphy exhibitions, displaying calligraphy works of famous Taoist articles. The Tea Garden and the Laozhuang Academy together form a "dynamic-static" combination of leisure and cultural system in Qingyang Palace - the halls are "dynamic" religious and cultural spaces, and the tea garden and academy are "static" cultural leisure spaces, allowing visitors to find a quiet place in the hustle and bustle of the city after pilgrimage and worship, and experience the "Taoist slow life".</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'area_tea_garden';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '藏经楼（宸经楼）',
  name_en = 'Sutra-Preservation Pavilion — Imperial Sutra Hall (Chenjing Hall)',
  body = '<p>The Canon Library, also called "Chenjing Lou," is the fifth hall on the central axis—originally built by Chan Master Cidu and rebuilt by Abbot Benyuan in 1824. Standing 15.84 m tall in two stories, it is the monastery''s central repository for sutras and treasures. The name "Chenjing" comes from Kangxi''s imperial calligraphy. Beyond the Ming and Qing Buddhist canons (Long, Pingqia, Taisho, Qianlong Da Zangjing and continuations), the library preserves Kangxi''s "Konglin" hand and his Mi Fu-style "Hai Yue" calligraphy, Song dragon ink paintings, late-Ming and Qing calligraphy by Poshan and Zhangxue, paintings by Biyan and Zhuchan, and works by He Shaoji, Zheng Banqiao, Zhang Daqian, and Feng Zikai. To the left rests a portion of the cranial relic of Master Xuanzang, transferred from Nanjing in the 1940s—the monk was ordained in Chengdu and lived here for five years; to the right rests a Buddha Śarīra brought from Bodh Gaya by the monk Nenghai in the 1920s. The "Tian Yi Xuan Cai" qipao embroidered with 248 Buddha figures by Ming consort Tian, the Qing hair-embroidered Water-Moon Guanyin, four blood-written sutras, and the Diamond Sutra pagoda painting—all part of the "Eight Views of Konglin"—are also housed here.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'area_sutra_preservation_pavilion_imperial_sutra_hall_chenjing_hall';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '茶园与香斋堂',
  name_en = 'Tea Garden and Vegetarian Hall',
  body = '<p>The Tea Garden sits inside the monastery''s east garden, opened in 1988 alongside the Thousand-Buddha Peace Pagoda, and operates as a "Chan-monastery teahouse" in old-Chengdu style. Bamboo roofs, blue-brick paving, square tables, covered-bowl tea, and long-spouted copper kettles recreate a classic "bada cha" open-air teahouse serving Bi Tan Piao Xue, Zhu Ye Qing, Mao Feng, Tie Guan Yin, and Pu''er teas at around RMB 10–30 per person, with free hot-water refills and outside snacks allowed. The Xiangzhai Hall vegetarian restaurant sits next to the Tea Garden and is separate from the monks'' Wuguan Hall. The menu emphasizes Sichuan-style vegetarian cuisine: vegetarian Mapo tofu, vegetarian twice-cooked pork, sweet rice cake, monastery pickles, and full vegetarian set meals at RMB 20–60 per person, plus luohan noodles and mushroom wonton. Together they create a "worship, tea, dine" loop, expressing the monastery''s "humanistic Buddhism" approach. Just outside the gate, Wenshu Yuan Street hosts Chengdu classics such as Long Chaoshou (Wenshu Yuan main branch), Yan Taipo Guokui, and Zhong Sui Jiao, making the visit a combined temple-and-old-streets experience.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'area_tea_garden_and_vegetarian_hall';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '大雄宝殿',
  name_en = 'Mahavira Hall (Great Buddha Hall / Precious Hall of the Great Hero)',
  body = '<p>The Mahavira Hall is the third hall on the central axis, originally built by Chan Master Cidu and rebuilt by Abbot Zhangbai. Standing 10.56 m tall in single-eaved Xieshan style, it is the largest and highest-ranked hall in the monastery. The central glass shrine houses a bronze Sakyamuni Buddha cast in 1829, flanked by bronze Kasyapa and Ananda figures—the most important Qing-dynasty bronze trio in the monastery and part of the "Eight Views of Konglin." Two Burmese jade Buddhas brought back in 1923 and 1938 by monks Xinglin and Dengyun sit in the shrine ("Burmese Jade in the Shrine"). Two ancient fir trees, each 15 m tall, stand behind the hall: descendants of the firs that flanked the old gate and under which Master Cidu took shelter ("Twin Firs Auspicious"). Free incense is provided—one stick per person, taken with both hands.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'area_mahavira_hall_great_buddha_hall_precious_hall_of_the_great_hero';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '千佛和平塔与碑廊',
  name_en = 'Thousand Buddha Peace Pagoda and Stele Corridor',
  body = '<p>The Thousand-Buddha Peace Pagoda stands in the eastern courtyard between the Canon Library and Wenshu Pavilion. Built in 1988, it was inscribed and coupleted by Zhao Puchu, then president of the Buddhist Association of China. The six-sided, eleven-story iron pagoda rises 21 meters and bears 1,000 cast Buddha images. Six dragons crown the spire with bells that ring in the wind. The east, west, and north sides are lined with stele corridors displaying dozens of stone tablets—Qing imperial and official inscriptions, poems by the monastery''s abbots Cidu, Benyuan, Xuanlin, Nenghai, Biannen, and Weixian, and Buddhist maxims. The two-tiered surrounding walls are decorated with four-season floral motifs and bas-reliefs of the Journey to the West, symbolizing the two-way transmission of dharma along the Silk Road. Ginkgo, camphor, plum, and magnolia trees frame the pagoda, making it the monastery''s most contemplative garden.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'area_thousand_buddha_peace_pagoda_and_stele_corridor';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '三大士殿（观音殿）',
  name_en = 'wenshuyuan sub area 01',
  body = '<p>The Hall of the Three Great Beings, also called the Hall of Guanyin, is the second hall on the central axis and the only one of the six that retains its original 1697 Kangxi-period structure. Three principal statues stand on a central platform: Manjushri on a blue lion (wisdom), Guanyin holding a willow branch and pure-water vase (compassion), and Samantabhadra on a white elephant (vow and action). Side bays house Wenchang Dijun and Saintly Lord Guan, reflecting the late-imperial Sichuanese fusion of Buddhist, Daoist, and Confucian popular devotion. Behind the hall stands the bronze Weituo guardian, cast by Abbot Benyuan in 1829. The lintel couplet by late-Qing Chengdu literatus Fang Hezhai—"What is done let be done, what is let go let be let go, what ends, ends; wisdom is born of awakening, awakening is born of ease, what arises, arises and yet does not arise"—expresses the Chan spirit of resolving the matter at hand.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'wenshuyuan_sa_01';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '山门（天王殿）',
  name_en = 'Mountain Gate — Heavenly Kings Hall (Tianwang Hall)',
  body = '<p>The Main Gate / Hall of Heavenly Kings is the first hall on the central axis, originally built by Chan Master Cidu and rebuilt by Abbot Benyuan, facing south with a five-bay facade in classic Kangxi–Daoguang Sichuanese style. The gate and hall are combined: the two Heng-Ha guardians stand at the door, Maitreya is enshrined at the center (with Weituo behind), and the Four Heavenly Kings—Dhṛtarāṣṭra, Virūḍhaka, Virūpākṣa, and Vaiśravaṇa—flank the hall, each holding a sword, pipa, parasol, or serpent/dragon to symbolize favorable weather. The pillars bear the couplet by Qing abbot Fu Wenjiwei. In front, the three-story Drum and Bell towers face each other: the bell tower houses a 4,500+ kg Qing-dynasty bronze bell, the drum tower its great drum. Their morning bell and evening drum mark the monastic schedule and ritual calendar.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'area_mountain_gate_heavenly_kings_hall_tianwang_hall';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '说法堂（药师殿）',
  name_en = 'Dharma Preaching Hall — Medicine Master Hall (Bhaisajyaguru Hall)',
  body = '<p>The Dharma Hall, also called the Hall of Bhaisajyaguru, is the fourth hall on the central axis and is said to occupy the site of the original Tang-era Xinxiang Monastery. A double-eaved Xieshan Qing-dynasty building, it contains a brick ordination platform used for precepts ceremonies, lay refuge, and sutra lectures. At center, beneath a jeweled canopy, sits Bhaisajyaguru, the Medicine Buddha of the eastern Lapis Lazuli world, flanked by the twelve yakṣa generals—each guarding one of the twelve时辰 hours and zodiac animals. The back wall bears the Kangxi Emperor''s 1702 inscription "Konglin" (Empty Forest)—the calligraphic origin of the monastery''s alternate name "Konglin Tang" and the first of the "Eight Views of Konglin." The Sichuanese-style Buddhist chanting preserved here was inscribed on Chengdu''s seventh intangible cultural heritage list in 2021.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'area_dharma_preaching_hall_medicine_master_hall_bhaisajyaguru_hall';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '文殊阁',
  name_en = 'Wenshu Pavilion',
  body = '<p>Wenshu Pavilion stands at the northernmost end of the central axis. Built in 1997 under the 17th abbot Xuanlin, it occupies about 1,000 square meters in a three-story Qing-style double-eave structure. The first floor, the "Konglin Lecture Hall," seats several hundred for dharma talks, meditation, and Chan practice. The second floor houses the "Konglin Buddhist Library," with sutras, modern Buddhist scholarship, and journals for both laypeople and researchers. The third floor, the "Ten-Thousand-Buddha Hall," enshrines the central principal Buddha surrounded by a thousand Buddhas on the four walls, creating the monastery''s most contemplative space. The pavilion closes the central axis and complements the five earlier historic halls, forming a "front-court, rear-market" plan that joins devotional and cultural functions.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'area_wenshu_pavilion';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '园林与放生池',
  name_en = 'Garden and Life-Releasing Pond',
  body = '<p>The Wenshu Monastery gardens center on the east and west gardens flanking the central axis and the Release Pond—landscaped together with the Thousand-Buddha Pagoda in 1988. The Release Pond sits between the Hall of Heavenly Kings and the Mahavira Hall in an irregular L shape, home to koi, goldfish, and turtles, with water lilies, calamus, and willows along the banks; a Qing-era "Release Pond" stele stands on the north bank in Manchu and Chinese. The Tingsong Waterside Pavilion on the west bank responds visually to the Bell and Drum towers. The east garden ("Hearing and Reflecting") and west garden ("Cultivating and Realizing") flank the central axis, with Taihu rocks, ginkgo, camphor, plum, magnolia, crepe myrtle, and paths of bamboo. Covered corridors tie the halls, gardens, and the Peace Pagoda into a single meandering composition. The two ancient firs at the rear of the Mahavira Hall, said to mark Master Cidu''s hermitage, are the "Twin Firs Auspicious" of the "Eight Views of Konglin."</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'area_garden_and_life_releasing_pond';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '正门（照壁）',
  name_en = 'Main Gate — Screen Wall',
  body = '<p>The front gate and spirit wall stand at the south end of the Wenshu Monastery central axis, the first visual anchor before visitors reach the main gate. About 8 meters high and shaped like the character "pin" (品) in brick and stone, the wall is inscribed with the three characters "Wénshū Yuàn" and the couplet "Ruìzé shēn tiāndì, zōngfēng yuè gǔjīn" (Wisdom deep as heaven and earth, lineage surpassing past and present), said to be in the hand of Chan Master Cidu of the Kangxi reign. The wall faces the city street on one side and the temple gate on the other—a classic Chinese monastic gesture of modesty and containment. Two side gates flank the central entrance, and the temple itself is open and free, with the public transit and city road reaching right up to the wall.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'area_main_gate_screen_wall';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '九街标志牌坊',
  name_en = 'Jiujie Gateway Archway',
  body = '<p>The Jiujie Gateway Archway stands at the entrance of Guanyinqiao Jiujie, serving as the symbolic portal of this renowned nightlife district. Built in traditional Chinese architectural style with upturned eaves, painted beams, and the characters "Jiujie" inscribed at the center, it exudes grandeur. By day, the archway appears stately and classical; by night, illuminated lights blend with surrounding neon, creating a striking fusion of old and new. As the landmark of Jiujie, it is a must-visit photo spot for tourists and the starting point for exploring the area''s vibrant nightlife. Surrounded by shops and restaurants ranging from traditional hotpot to trendy bars, it is the perfect gateway to experience Chongqing''s urban night culture.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_jiujie_sa_01';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '九街高屋',
  name_en = 'Jiujie High House',
  body = '<p>KTV和live house等娱乐场所，是年轻人夜间社交的热门聚集地。高屋内还设有多个主题露台，可俯瞰整个九街繁华夜景。无论是品尝创意料理、欣赏现场音乐，还是与朋友畅饮小聚，九街高屋都能提供一站式的都市夜生活体验，是感受重庆不夜城魅力的必访之地。 Jiujie High House is one of the most iconic commercial complexes in the Guanyinqiao Jiujie business district, renowned for its distinctive high-rise facade and diverse mix of businesses. The building features a modern glass curtain wall exterior with dazzling nighttime lighting, forming a brilliant highlight in the Jiujie skyline. Inside, it houses popular internet-famous restaurants, trendy boutique shops, KTV venues, and live houses, making it a hotspot for young people''s nightlife socializing. Multiple themed terraces offer panoramic views of the bustling Jiujie nightscape. Whether enjoying creative cuisine, live music, or drinks with friends, Jiujie High House provides a one-stop urban nightlife experience and is a must-visit destination to feel the charm of Chongqing''s sleepless city.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_jiujie_sa_02';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '鲤鱼池42号文创园',
  name_en = 'Liyuchi No. 42 Cultural and Creative Park',
  body = '<p>Liyuchi No. 42 Cultural and Creative Park was formerly an old industrial factory in Chongqing. After careful renovation, it has been revitalized into a cultural space combining art exhibitions, creative design, specialty dining, and leisure entertainment. The park preserves the rugged framework of the original industrial architecture, with red brick walls and steel structures complementing each other. Weathered traces of time blend ingeniously with modern art installations, creating a unique retro-artistic atmosphere. The park houses numerous independent designer studios, handicraft workshops, boutique cafés, and niche art galleries, and regularly hosts creative markets and art salons. Large-scale graffiti murals on weathered walls are popular photo backdrops for young visitors. Away from the bustle of Jiujie, it offers a quiet, inspiration-filled haven for art and creativity lovers.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_jiujie_sa_03';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '九街后街',
  name_en = 'Jiujie Back Street',
  body = '<p>Jiujie Back Street refers to the alleyway area behind Jiujie''s main street, offering a stark contrast to the neon-lit bustle of the main thoroughfare with a more authentic taste of everyday Chongqing life. Narrow alleys are lined with small food shops serving local delicacies—from steaming bowls of hot and sour noodles and soft glutinous rice cakes to sizzling skewers and fragrant tofu noodles—gathering the most genuine flavors of Chongqing''s streets. There are no upscale restaurants here, only the most down-to-earth tastes and the warmest proprietors. Many locals'' late-night favorites are hidden in these alleys, where an unassuming shop may have been passed down for decades. Walls are adorned with lively graffiti and old-Chongqing-themed murals. Strolling through feels like stepping into a vivid scroll painting of Ba-Yu street life, making it the perfect place to experience authentic Chongqing food culture and neighborhood charm.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_jiujie_sa_04';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '十八梯大牌坊',
  name_en = 'Shiba Ti Grand Archway',
  body = '<p>The Shiba Ti Grand Archway stands at the southern entrance of the Shiba Ti Traditional Heritage District, serving as the first landmark for visitors entering this century-old street. Built from blue stone in a four-pillar, three-bay sky-reaching style, it stands over ten meters tall—imposing yet refined and elegant. The central plaque is inscribed with three gold-leaf characters reading "Shiba Ti," while the crossbeams feature relief carvings of bats, auspicious clouds, and ruyi patterns. The stone-drum pillar bases are finely carved, combining the robustness of Ba-Yu stone carving with the gracefulness of southern Chinese archways. A small plaza surrounds the archway with faux-antique stone paving, ficus bonsai, and decorative lamp posts. After dark, warm yellow lights illuminate the stone structure, creating a rich atmosphere of old Yuzhou charm. Looking north from here, the main street of Shiba Ti unfolds in cascading stone steps descending the hillside, with stilt-house-style shops lining both sides, and modern skyscrapers in the distance overlapping with tiled eaves nearby. A guide map and electronic touch screen beside the archway mark all attractions and recommended routes, making it an essential stop for planning visits and taking photos.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_shibati_sa_01';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '善果巷与山城记忆馆',
  name_en = 'Shanguo Lane and Mountain City Memory Hall',
  body = '<p>Shanguo Lane is a historic stone-step alley within the Shiba Ti Heritage District. Its name originates from the Shanguo Temple that once stood here during the Qing Dynasty, carrying forward the spirit of charity and goodwill. The alley is about two meters wide, bordered by old brick walls and stone embankments intertwined with ficus tree roots, covered in moss and draped with vines—walking through it feels like traveling back to the slow-paced old Chongqing. Within the lane sits the Mountain City Memory Hall, a micro-museum converted from a traditional residence. With its grey tiles, white walls, and wooden windows, the exterior is understated, yet stepping inside reveals a hidden world. The hall uses "Upper City and Lower City" as its theme, presenting through old photographs, vintage objects, oral history videos, and interactive installations the century-long evolution of Shiba Ti—from the bustling pier trade of the late Qing and early Republic, through the wartime capital''s population surge, to modern urban renewal. Exhibits include old kerosene lamps, bamboo-woven thermos flasks, hand-written street signs, and yellowed household registers—everyday objects full of warmth that bear authentic witness to ordinary Chongqing residents'' lives. A "sound wall" features recordings of street hawker cries, work chants, and riverboat whistles—put on the headphones and listen to the vanishing sounds of the mountain city.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_shibati_sa_02';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '月台坝（山地院落）',
  name_en = 'Yuetai Ba (Mountain Courtyard)',
  body = '<p>Yuetai Ba is located mid-way along Shiba Ti—a cluster of terraced courtyard residences naturally formed by the hillside gradient, and one of the nodes that best embodies Chongqing''s mountain architecture within the entire heritage district. The name "Yuetai" (Moon Platform) comes from the broad, flat stone platform in front of the courtyards, shaped like a moon terrace. In the past, residents gathered here to cool off, chat, dry laundry, and let children play—it was the heart of neighborhood social life. The courtyard complex features timber frame structures with blue brick and stone walls, stepping down the slope in successive terraces. Looking up from below, rows of grey-tiled eaves rise like steps; looking down from above, courtyards, skylights, and stone stairs interlock in rich spatial layers. After renovation, Yuetai Ba retains its original architectural bones and spatial fabric, with damaged components restored using traditional craftsmanship, while new businesses—creative shops, teahouses, and craft workshops—have been introduced. Narrow stone-step alleys connect the courtyards, with stone water vats and ficus bonsai at corners, revealing the old Chongqing philosophy of "climbing slopes and turning corners" everywhere. Sitting in a bamboo chair on the moon platform with a bowl of covered tea, overlooking the half-cityscape and distant river views, is the most authentic way to experience the slow life of the mountain city.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_shibati_sa_03';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '大隧道遗址',
  name_en = 'Great Tunnel Relics',
  body = '<p>The Shiba Ti Great Tunnel Relics are a vital part of Chongqing''s WWII air defense engineering. After the Nationalist Government relocated the capital to Chongqing in 1937, Japanese forces conducted indiscriminate strategic bombing of the city for five and a half years. To protect civilian lives, Chongqing mobilized the entire city to excavate a massive network of air-raid shelter tunnels. The Shiba Ti Great Tunnel was one of these, approximately 2 km long, carved by hand into sandstone hillside. The interior stands about 2 meters high and 2–3 meters wide, capable of sheltering thousands simultaneously. The tunnel was equipped with ventilation shafts, drainage channels, rest areas, and rudimentary medical stations—crude conditions that nonetheless saved countless lives during the darkest years. The now-open section has been safety-reinforced and scenically restored. Chisel marks and smoke stains from the era remain visible on the walls. Information panels and multimedia installations inside detail the historical background of the Chongqing Bombing, the tunnel construction process, and civilian shelter life. Walking through, one hears simulated air-raid sirens and infants'' cries, creating a profound sense of the resilience and survival spirit of the Chongqing people during those fiery years—a historically educational immersive site.</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_shibati_sa_04';

UPDATE sub_areas SET
  name_zh = '名字：宝顶山',
  name_en = 'Baoding Mountain',
  body = '<p>U 字形马蹄形山湾，长约 500 米、高 8—15 米的崖壁上环列 31 组大型造像，题材前后连接、起承转合，将佛教教义、世俗生活与民间故事融为一体，被誉为"中国晚期石窟艺术集大成之作"和"中国石窟艺术史上最后一座丰碑"。1999 年 12 月，宝顶山摩崖造像作为"大足石刻"的组成部分被联合国教科文组织列入《世界遗产名录》。</p>',
  updated_at = NOW()
WHERE id = 'chongqing_dazu_rock_carvings_sa_01';

